It is not dangerous! What people need to do is learn how to drive and 
respect speed limits. It's only dangerous if you place yourself in that 
situation. The speed limit for those exit and entrance ramps is 25mph. And 
if you're emerging into the freeway, it is your responsibility to give the 
right of way to traffic on the left if they're coming out fast and/or you 
need to speed up if they're exiting slow but once you're out of the loop. I 
never have a problem exiting and entering the freeway through those ramps. 
I've been living in Lynwood for over 20 years and I know that ramp like the 
palm of my hand, the only time there are accidents is when there are 
wreckless drivers on those ramps. On the night of Black Friday in 2012, I 
witness a man dive his car in the ditch when he got on the ramp getting out 
of the 710 NB towards W Imperial Hwy, he was going more than 70mph. It is 
not the ramps, it is the drivers.

I understand that there's nothing they can do for her, but why is it that 
firefighters always look like they're working so slowly? Even in house 
fires I've seen, it looks like they're just strolling along like they have 
all day. I work in construction -- not exactly what you'd call an emergency 
situation -- and yet if I moved this slowly on the job, I'd get fired.

I'm sure there's a reason for it... just don't know what it is.﻿

+Marina Somes I was about to mention the important distinction but 
fortunately you did it. Emotional shock can cause nausea, fainting, 
anxiety, but these are not precursors to a life threatening condition as 
may occur from physical shock. Scores of people suffer from things like 
generalized anxiety disorder and panic attacks and although these are very 
unpleasant and even debilitating conditions, they are not life threatening.

+Far Sight Sometimes asking questions can relieve psychological stress or

+Far Sight Just a btw. He is in a state of shock not physically in shock. 
People often confuse being "shocked" with physiological shock, which is 
simply hypoperfusion (Inadequate oxygenation of the bodies cells and 
tissues). The signs and symptoms of true shock will always include Pale 
skin, Sweating and rapid/weak pulse. The mental state of shock that the man 
is in can not be treated because there is no physiological aspect causing 
it.

+Far Sight shock from witnessing an accident is different that the

+The1GuyRuben Shock may result from trauma, heatstroke, blood loss, an 
allergic reaction, severe infection, poisoning, severe burns or other 
causes. When a person is in shock, his or her organs aren't getting enough 
blood or oxygen. If untreated, this can lead to permanent organ damage or 
even death.

Signs and symptoms of shock vary depending on circumstances and may include:

Cool, clammy skin
Pale or ashen skin
Rapid pulse
Rapid breathing
Nausea or vomiting
Enlarged pupils
Weakness or fatigue
Dizziness or fainting
Changes in mental status or behavior, such as anxiousness or agitation
Seek emergency medical care

If you suspect a person is in shock, call 911 or your local emergency 
number. Then immediately take the following steps:

Lay the person down and elevate the legs and feet slightly, unless you 
think this may cause pain or further injury.
Keep the person still and don't move him or her unless necessary.
Begin CPR if the person shows no signs of life, such as breathing, coughing 
or movement.
Loosen tight clothing and, if needed, cover the person with a blanket to 
prevent chilling.
Don't let the person eat or drink anything.
If the person vomits or begins bleeding from the mouth, turn him or her 
onto a side to prevent choking, unless you suspect a spinal injury.

of the door locking system. When you open the door of any car it is that 
silver or gray bolt the door latch locks onto. These bolts were installed 
to keep a car door from opening under low impact conditions. They work very 
well. The best way to defeat them is with the jaws of a Hurst tool.

doing is only going to wear you out.﻿
